Inside the information system itself, new forms of manipulation took root. CNN and CNBC announced partnerships with Kalshi, an online prediction market, to integrate real-time betting data into their news coverage. The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which regulates Kalshi, does not ban insider trading in the way the SEC does, and Kalshi\'92s own rules against trading on \'93material non-public information\'94 rest on uncertain enforcement. As a result, wealthy or well-connected actors could both shape events and bet on them, with their wagers displayed as \'93market expectations\'94 on major news networks. A separate study by the Network Contagion Research Institute documented how extremist Nick Fuentes\'92s social media reach had been artificially boosted by anonymous and foreign accounts, manufacturing influence through coordinated engagement. Together, these developments showed how data and algorithms could be used to distort public perception, while regulatory and editorial choices lagged behind. The information field is tilting.\
