The administration also moved to reshape symbols and memory. Plans to replace images of national parks on annual passes with Trump\'92s face, starting in 2026, prompted a lawsuit from the Center for Biological Diversity, which argued that federal law required the use of winning photos from a public contest. The National Trust for Historic Preservation sued to stop a $300 million White House ballroom project that would demolish part of the East Wing without the required reviews or congressional approval, citing violations of planning, environmental, and constitutional provisions. In both cases, public spaces and buildings were being reimagined as canvases for personal grandeur, with watchdogs forced to invoke long-standing statutes to slow the work. The fight is over symbols as well as statutes.\
\
Against this backdrop, there were real acts of resistance and adaptation. The Indiana Senate, including a majority of Republicans, rejected a Trump-backed mid-decade gerrymander despite explicit threats from the administration to withhold federal funds. Organizers in Missouri submitted more than 300,000 signatures to force a referendum on a gerrymandered congressional map, though the attorney general moved to block the vote and the secretary of state tried to discard signatures. In Miami, voters elected Eileen Higgins as the city\'92s first Democratic mayor in nearly thirty years, on a pro-immigrant platform, in a county Trump had carried. Churches across the country used nativity scenes to protest ICE actions, depicting a handcuffed baby Jesus and a gas-masked Mary. Immigrant-rights groups like Siembra trained business owners and municipal employees to insist on warrants before admitting federal agents. These were not structural counterweights, but they were signs that civil society and some state actors still understood the stakes and were willing to act. The civic muscle has not vanished.\
