In the courts, too, the picture was mixed. A New Jersey judge permanently barred former Senator Bob Menendez from holding state or local office after his corruption conviction, reinforcing consequences for abuse of public trust. A Louisiana pastor was convicted of indecent behavior with a juvenile, and an army gynecologist at Fort Hood faced a sweeping civil suit from 81 women alleging sexual abuse. Youth plaintiffs in Montana petitioned their state supreme court to enforce a prior ruling recognizing a constitutional right to a clean and healthful environment against new laws that tried to sidestep it. At the same time, the U.S. Supreme Court allowed Texas to use a congressional map a lower court had found likely discriminatory, and heard arguments that could give presidents broad power to remove independent agency heads. The same institution that sometimes checked overreach also opened doors to deeper politicization. The guardrail is uneven.\
