The Democracy Clock\'92s stillness at 8:11 p.m. in Week 47 should not be mistaken for safety. It reflects a moment when the architecture of this second Trump term is becoming more legible rather than more extreme: executive power stretched across war, trade, and technology; law bent to protect insiders and punish opponents; security forces and immigration systems used as instruments of political will; and money and media intertwined with governance to a degree that makes crony capitalism hard to distinguish from state policy. Courts, states, and civil society still find ways to resist, and sometimes they succeed. But the balance of power is shifting toward a model in which accountability is episodic and contingent, while impunity and stratification are built into the structure. That is what it means, in this week, for the clock to hold at 8:11 p.m.\'97not that time has stopped, but that the country is settling into a dangerous equilibrium.\
